I"E<h2 id="r2-value">\(R^2\) value</h2>

<ul>
  <li>In statistics, the <font color="red">coefficient of determination</font>, denoted R2 or r2 and pronounced “R squared”, is the proportion of the variance in the dependent variable that is predictable from the independent variable(s). For <font color="red">regression</font> for most cases.</li>
  <li>SStot is the total sum of squares:</li>
</ul>

<p>$SS_{tot}= \Sigma _i(y_i-\overline{y})^2$</p>

<ul>
  <li>SSres is the sum of squares of residuals:</li>
</ul>

<p>$SS_{res}= \Sigma _i(y_i-f_i)^2= \Sigma _ie_i^2$</p>

<p>$\overline{y}=\frac{1}{n} \Sigma _{i=1}^ny_i$</p>

<ul>
  <li>R^2 is calculated as the following:</li>
</ul>

<p>$R^2 \equiv 1-\frac{SS_{res}}{SS_{tot}}$</p>

<ul>
  <li>$R^2$ is used to measure how close the data are to the fitted regression line. Value [0,1], closer 1 means <font color="red">better</font>. $R^2$ = 1 indicates that the model explains all the variability of the response data around its mean.
